This paper deals with the computational complexity of a problem related to weighted voting games, which is a topic in computational social choice (cs.GT). The paper also involves analyzing the Shapley-Shubik and normalized Banzhaf indices, which are commonly used in voting theory and can be considered as topics in algorithms and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also involves analyzing the complexity of the problem, which can be considered as a topic in computational complexity theory (cs.CC). Additionally, the paper involves analyzing the probabilistic Banzhaf index, which can be considered as a topic in discrete mathematics (cs.DM). Finally, the paper involves analyzing the merging and splitting of players, which can be considered as a topic in data structures (cs.DS).
